\keepn \f15 \cf13 \fs36 \b \pard \keepn \f15 Unfragmenting\par \b0 \pard \f15 \fs28 \pard \f15 \b \cf0 What is 'Unfragmenting'?\par \b0 'Unfragmenting' is probably a slight misdescription.  Fragmented files are generally spread over a number of physical locations on a hard disk.  Conventional disk 'defragmentation' collects all these separate pieces and joins them into one single piece. The file is contiguous but it's size is the same.\par \par In contrast, UnfragWorks reduces the file size by removing redundant information whilst retaining the document information.\par \par \par \b How does it work?\par \b0 Every Microsoft compound document, that supports Object Linking and Embedding (OLE), such as SolidWorks files, can contain redundant information.  UnfragWorks removes this redundancy to dramatically reduce the overall file size.\par \par \par \b Is it safe?\par \b0 UnfragWorks Server has been tested, and works correctly, with the latest version of SolidWorks.  The only change to the SolidWorks file is in the file size.  All parametric information is preserved and no data is altered in any way.  UnfragWorks Server is 100% safe to use in a production environment.\par \par \page 
